Original 1.35.2 Release
=======================
The PILBox is a beautiful hardware now designed and built by Karel Koci. 
Il was originally designed by Jean-Francois Garnier.

This is the port of ilper-1.35 in C under Linux. One of tools used to manage
the PILBox and the HP-IL emulation.

Because I do not like Windows and I do not use it, I started to write the port of
the ilper executable under Linux.
It should work also under others *nix like the *BSD systems and MAC OS/X.

It is tested under Linux Debian Etch 4.0r5.
It has worked with a HP-75C and a HP-41CV + HP-82160A HP-IL module.
You need to have a HP-82160A HP-IL module with the HP-41C* calculator to use this
tool and the PILBox.

<< New >> in 1.40 version
=========================
- Resizable windows,
- LIF file selector,
- Serial USB Device selector,
- Serial USB Device selector,
- Designed for the HP-IL 80 Column Video Interface (MC00701A),
- Number of mnemos adjust to the Scope window size,
- Some colors.

Works well under Debian and other linuxes.
tested with a HP41, HP71. Try reversi game, very nice !

1/ REQUIREMENTS

  - It does not use X. So it may run on simple terminals.
  - It uses the NCURSES library.
  - It needs the FTDI serial driver to be installed. In the recent 
    linux version, the FTDI driver is embedded inside the kernel.

2/ INSTALLATION

Extract the tarball in a working directory :
   tar jxpf ilper-linux-<version>.tbz

Go the ilper directory and build the executable :
   cd ilper-linux-<version>
   make
   make install

It installs the ilper executable to $HOME/bin. To change the executable install
path, do :
   make INSTALLDIR=<path-to-install> install
The ilper will be copied to the directory <path-to-install>/bin.

Be sure that the FTDI driver is installed and look on which device is connected
the PILBox. It should be /dev/ttyUSB<x> where <x> is a number.
On my computer, it is /dev/ttyUSB0.
With the TULIP4041, drivers should be /dev/ttyACM<x> where <x> is a number.

It should appear in the dmesg buffer :
ohci_hcd 0000:00:02.0: wakeup
usb 2-9: new full speed USB device using ohci_hcd and address 2
usb 2-9: configuration #1 chosen from 1 choice
usbcore: registered new driver usbserial
drivers/usb/serial/usb-serial.c: USB Serial support registered for generic
usbcore: registered new driver usbserial_generic
drivers/usb/serial/usb-serial.c: USB Serial Driver core
drivers/usb/serial/usb-serial.c: USB Serial support registered for FTDI USB Serial Device
ftdi_sio 2-9:1.0: FTDI USB Serial Device converter detected
drivers/usb/serial/ftdi_sio.c: Detected FT232BM
usb 2-9: FTDI USB Serial Device converter now attached to ttyUSB0
usbcore: registered new driver ftdi_sio
drivers/usb/serial/ftdi_sio.c: v1.4.3:USB FTDI Serial Converters Driver

And an entry is added in /dev :
crw-rw---- 1 root dialout 188, 0 2011-03-31 21:09 /dev/ttyUSB0

or
crw-rw---- 1 root dialout 166, 0 Jul 23 18:36 /dev/ttyACM0
crw-rw---- 1 root dialout 166, 1 Jul 23 18:36 /dev/ttyACM1
crw-rw---- 1 root dialout 166, 2 Jul 23 18:36 /dev/ttyACM2
crw-rw---- 1 root dialout 166, 3 Jul 23 18:36 /dev/ttyACM3
crw-rw---- 1 root dialout 166, 4 Jul 23 18:36 /dev/ttyACM4

To access the /dev/ttyUSB<x> or /dev/ttyACM<x> device, the user should belong 
to the dialout group.

By default, the PILBox device is /dev/ttyUSB0 and the LIF file is HDRIVE1.DAT.
This may be overwritten by setting the ILDEVICE=<device> or ILDISK=<LIF file>
variables when launching make.

To build ilper with the device '/dev/ttyUSB6', do make ILDEVICE=/dev/ttyUSB6
To build ilper with the LIF file 'mydisk.lif', do make ILDISK=mydisk.lif

If your terminal is badly configured, the border windows decoration may look
strange and unreadable. In this case, just recompile the ilper sofware by setting
the option USEASCII. To do so, make clean && make USEASCII=yes

Take care of doing a make clean before changing ILDEVICE or ILDISK, or by setting
or clearing the option USEASCII.

3/ USAGE

To run just launch the ilper tool with
  <path of ilper>/ilper

The ilper will show 3 windows as follow:
+-------------------------------[ ILPER 1.40.0 ]--------------------------------+
| +-[ Mass Storage LIF File ]---------+   +-[ PILBox Link ]-------+             |
| |LIF:HDRIVE1.DAT                    |   |Device:/dev/ttyUSB0    |     [STOP ] |
| +-----------------------------------+   +-----------------------+             |
+-[ Display ]---------------------------+-[ Scope:scope.out ]-------------------+
|                                       | IFC      AAU      AAD 01   TAD 01     |
|T=  0.0000                             | SAI      DAB 2E   UNL      LAD 01     |
|Z=  0.0000                             | UNL      AAU      AAD 01   TAD 01     |
|Y=  0.0000                             | SAI      DAB 2E   LAD 01   UNL        |
|X=  0.0000                             | AAU      AAD 01   TAD 01   SAI        |
|                                       | DAB 2E   LAD 01   DAB 0D   DAB 0A     |

The top window shows the current LIF file used, the current device where the
PILBox is connected and the state of emulation STARTed or STOPped.
The reverse video field is the active one. To select another field, use the TAB
key or SHIFT+TAB key.
To change the value of LIF or Device, press ENTER, enter the new value and
press ENTER to set. The START or STOP, just press ENTER as a flip-flop.

The following commands are accepted:
  h - Display a help
  v - Display the software version
  a - Start the emulation
  o - Stop the emulation
  l - Change the LIF File (Edit)
  L - Select the LIF File (Browser)
  p - Change the device for the PILBox Link
  s - Enable/Disable the HP-IL scope mode
  S - Enable/Disable the HP-IL scope recording into the file scope.out
  d - Toggle between default Display (PRINTER) and Video interface MC00701A
  D - Enable/Disable the HP-IL display recording into the file display.out
  q or Q - Close the PILBox and exit

To select a LIF FIle instead of entering its name, press the "L" key.
You enter in a file browser. The following commands are:
  <Left arrow>	 to go to parent directory
  <Right Arrow>  to enter selected directory
  <Enter> 	 to select the file
  <Q>	   	 to quit without selecting a file (Filename is not changed)

The left bottom window is the display area. It works as a printer or a video
device. Press "d" to toggle between normal Display mode and a MC00701A interface
with enhanced video mode. Default display is enhanced mode
(see for example http://www.series80.org/Misc/MC00701A.pdf)
Display recoding works only with normal display.

The right bottom window is the scope window and it prints all the frames
seen on the HP-IL. By default the scope window is hidden. You can enable/disable
it by using the "s" command. "S" command only works when Scope window is enabled.

To exit from ilper, just press Q or q. Confirm by choosing Y or N.

4/ IMPORTANT

The windows are dynamically resized when you change the terminal size.
The display and scope windows content are cleared once resized.

The footer displays a short help on the left and the terminal size on the right.
The terminal size becomes red when terminal size is less then 80x24

Be careful to not resize the terminal window when in LIF File browser mode.

The defaut baud rate is now set to 115200 bauds to work with a PILBOX.
Maybe not yet optimized, but fully functional.


